          SECTION 1.0 OVERVIEW          ____________________

          VAL runs in a TYMNET Engine ISIS job slot and allows users to update
          the Controlling User Directory (CUD) on disk.  VAL also has instruc-
          tions to back up the CUD to  magnetic tape and  to  restore the  CUD
          from tape.  If there is more than one supervisor in a network, there
          will be  copies of  the CUD  on   all  supervisor   systems.   These
          copies  are  called  Master User  Directories, or MUDs.  In addition
          to  the instructions  described below,  if  there are  MUDs  to   be
          updated,  VAL records  all   changes  made  to  the  CUD   to a spe-
          cial disk area.

          VAL also provides an optional facility for users to change their own
          passwords.


          SECTION 1.1 Login          _________________

          VAL runs in an ISIS job slot and  may be accessed by either a privi-
          leged or  unprivileged username.   To log into  VAL the  user should
          enter:

                                   NETVAL;password

                                        or

                                   NETPRIV;password

          NETVAL is  the unprivileged username  and NETPRIV is  the privileged
          username.

          When a user  is successfully logged into VAL,  the following message
          will be output:

                    ISIS Network Validation System Version 3.03

          Only one  user at a time  may be running  in VAL.  If a  second user
          tries to log in, the following message will be output:

                    VAL ALREADY RUNNING

          and the circuit will be zapped.














