          SECTION 1.2 CUD Entries          _______________________

          Optional CUD entries will  be included unless VAL  has been specifi-
          cally set to ignore options.  The  Home System and Class Information
          options  are mutually  exclusive and  the choice  between these  two
          options must be made at system  generation time.  The account repre-
          sentative must be  contacted to have any of the  options changed.  A
          CUD entry may consist of:

          1. USERNAME
             A username may be up  to 20 alphanumeric characters.  Semicolons,
             colons, and all control characters  are not acceptable characters
             for usernames.

          2. PASSWORD CIPHER
             The password cipher  is  computed  from  a  password   of  up  to
             30  characters.  Any  ASCII  character  other than  a  semicolon,
             Escape, or carriage return may be  used within a password.  Pass-
             words are not  echoed to the terminal, and are  entered twice for
             verification.

          3. PASSWORD CHANGE DATE
             The change date is the date that the password was last changed.

          4. GLOBAL ACCOUNT NUMBER (GAN) - OPTIONAL
             The GAN is  an octal number between 0 and   37777777777  and  may
             be used to group users together.

          5. UNIVERSAL USER NUMBER (UUN)
             The  UUN is  an octal  number between  0 and  37777777777 and  is
             unique for each user.

          6. CONTROL INFORMATION:

             IGNORE COLON OPTION (OPTIONAL)
             If the ignore colon option is set,  the user may  only  log  into
             his home system.

             LOGIN OVER SHUT (OPTIONAL)
             Login over shut allows users to access  a  host  even  if  it  is
             shut.

             NO PASSWORD (OPTIONAL)
             If the no password option is  set,  users  are  not  required  to
             input  a  password   when they login and the user  may only login
             to his home system.  (This command implies ignore colon option.)

             TRANSPARENT GATEWAY LOGON (OPTIONAL)
             If the  transparent gateway logon option  is set, the  user logon
             will take him through a gateway into another network.  (This com-
             mand implies ignore colon option.)



                                                            OVERVIEW    Page 2


          VAL Users Guide                                   September 26, 1980



          7. DISTRICT (OPTIONAL)
             The  district is  a  decimal number  between 0  and  4095 and  is
             another way to group users together.

          8. IRC (OPTIONAL)
             The International  Record Carrier is  a decimal number  between 0
             and 127.   IRC tables must  be present  for any value  other than
             zero to be significant.  The  IRC tables designate unique numbers
             that have been  assigned to IRC links  and this CUD entry  may be
             used to limit  a user's circuit building to links  of a specified
             IRC.

          THE NEXT TWO OPTIONS ARE MUTUALLY  EXCLUSIVE AND ARE CHOSEN WHEN VAL
          IS INSTALLED IN THE NETWORK.  THE INSTRUCTIONS FOR CLASS INFORMATION
          WILL ONLY WORK IF THAT OPTION WAS CHOSEN.

          9. HOME SYSTEM (OPTIONAL)
             The CUD  must include either  class definitions or  home systems.
             Home systems entries in the CUD do not restrict user access.

          10. CLASS INFORMATION (OPTIONAL)

             The class  information option may be  used to establish  a closed
             user group within the network.  A  closed user group is a segment
             of the total  user population having more  restrictions placed on
             their activities within the network than those put on the general
             category of users.

             CLASS
             The class  for a user  represents the  set of node  numbers  from
             which  the  user may access the  network.  Each class is followed
             by up to six groups or hosts  describing which hosts the user may
             access.  Each class must have either a  home host or a home group
             defined.  Class 0 is the universal class.

             GROUP
             A group represents a set of host numbers.  Group 0 is the univer-
             sal group.

             HOST
             A host is a host number in the network.















