          SECTION 1.3 Format and Syntax          _____________________________



          1.3.1 Format                ______

          Val issues an asterisk, "*", to prompt the user to enter an instruc-
          tion.  After  an instruction has been  entered, VAL may  then prompt
          the user for  parameters.  The prompts may be  questions or requests
          and all require some form of response.

          A '?' response to any yes/no question  or prompt for a numeric value
          will  cause the   program  to   return  to   the  instruction   dis-
          patcher.  The  Control-A character  may be used  to delete  the last
          character typed when entering information.

          On two word instructions, such as CHANGE or TYPE, if the second word
          is not   entered,  VAL   will  output  the   options  to   the user.
          For example, if the user types NEW <CR>, VAL will output:

                    USER, OR CLASS:

          The user only needs to input 'USER'  or  'CLASS'  to  continue exec-
          ution of this instruction.

          On instructions  that change the  CUD, after  all   the  information
          is entered, the program prompts:

                    ALL ENTRIES CORRECT?

          If all the entered  information is as it should be,  the user should
          answer 'Y' and the instruction will be carried out.

                    ENTRY COMPLETED

          will then print  to the user when the operation  has been  completed
          sucessfully.   If some  entered information is in  error, answer 'N'
          and the program  will  return  to  the   instruction  dispatcher  to
          allow  the user to reenter the instruction.


          1.3.2 Syntax                ______

          The following  notation is used  in the instruction  descriptions to
          describe the syntax of the instructions:

          uppercase           Letters  or words  are entered  exactly as  they
                              appear in the syntax description.

          lowercase           Letters are optional entries as  VAL will recog-
                              nize instructions abbreviated  to their shortest
                              unique  length.   For  example,   CHEck  may  be
                              entered as  CHE, CHAnge may  be entered  as CHA,
                              and PASSword may be entered as PASS.


