          SECTION 5.0 INITIALIZING THE CUD          ________________________________

          When a  network is initially brought  up, there are no  usernames in
          the CUD.  Thus, it  is not possible to use the network  to log in to
          VAL and  validate usernames.   It is, however,  possible to  use the
          ISIS console TTY port to log in to an ISIS slot.  The following pro-
          cedure should be  used to initialize the CUD and  validate the first
          username.

               Connect a terminal  to the console TTY  port and log in  to the
               slot in which VAL is loaded.

               Example:

                  LOGON: mike
                  NODE:  2001
                  HOST:  121

                  SLOT #: 5
                  *

               Enter the  ?STAT command to start  up the procedure  and answer
               "YES" to the question.

               Example:

                  *?STAT

                  ISIS NETWORK VALIDATION SYSTEM VERSION 3.03

                  DO YOU WISH TO INITIALIZE THE CUD? y

               After a  few minutes  the program  will print  some message  to
               indicate completion.

               Example:

                  CUD HAS BEEN CLEARED INITIALIZING PJ AREA.
                  INITIALIZATION COMPLETE AND NETPRIV VALIDATED.
                  *

          At this point, the CUD has been cleared and the username NETPRIV has
          been validated.  With the initial password  of PRIVILEGE, it is then
          possible to use the network to log in to VAL to validate other user-
          names.

          To maintain network security, the  password for the NETPRIV username
          should be changed to another value  after CUD initialization is com-
          plete.







